<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900807-0043</DOCNO><DOCID>900807-0043.</DOCID><HL>   Big Board to Fine U.S. Unit   Of Nomura Securities Co.</HL><DATE>08/07/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12</SO><CO>   J.NOM</CO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- The U.S. subsidiary of Nomura Securities Co.will be fined $180,000 and censured by the New York StockExchange for alleged violations of exchange rules, accordingto people familiar with the case.   A hearing is scheduled for today to examine a settlementsurrounding allegations that Nomura Securities InternationalInc., the U.S. unit of the giant Japanese securities firm in1987 violated net capital requirements. These involvesituations where a firm allows its net capital to fall belowlevels prescribed by the exchange.</LP><TEXT>   People familiar with the case said the violations wererelatively small, involving several hundred thousand dollars.   As in most disciplinary cases, Nomura will settle withoutadmitting or denying wrongdoing, according to individualsfamiliar with the case. A Nomura spokesman declined tocomment; so did an exchange spokeswoman.   While not the biggest fine, the penalty would be one ofthe steepest leveled against a Big Board member firm. Since1987, the exchange and other &quot;self-regulators&quot; of the marketshave been under increased pressure to impose stiffer finesfor violators of market rules.   Last month, the New York Stock Exchange censured AmericanExpress Co.'s Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. unit and fined ita record $500,000 in a case involving Shearson's trading ofE.F. Hutton andamp; Co. stock during 1986 takeover talks.</TEXT></DOC>